<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,152,791]" pageId="8" pageNumber="107">
<emphasis box="[199,313,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="107">Genitalia.</emphasis>
Aedeagus stout (Fig. 7). Phallobase about 1.5x longer and a little wider than paramere bases together. Parameres each blade-like, inner surface concave, in dorsal view each with an inward-facing tooth just before apex; teeth overlapping, apices capable of contacting each other; in lateral view each paramere wide, ventral surface nearly straight, dorsal surface broadly arcuate, paramere tip blunt. Penis 3/4 or more length of paramere, terminating just before paramere teeth; in dorsal view wider than paramere at midlength; evenly tapered to a slightly produced, blunt apex; dorsum longitudinally carinate. Note: The specimen no longer appears as in Fig. 6. In order to dissect the genitalia, the specimen was removed from the original pin and later remounted on a pinned card point along with abdominal ventrites 3–5; the aedeagus is stored in glycerine in a genitalia vial pinned beneath the specimen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,152,791]" pageId="8" pageNumber="107">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,495,440,467]" pageId="8" pageNumber="107">Geographic distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from 
<collectingCountry box="[708,822,441,467]" name="Colombia" pageId="8" pageNumber="107">Colombia</collectingCountry>
. Because the specific 
<typeStatus box="[1066,1114,441,467]" pageId="8" pageNumber="107">type</typeStatus>
locality is unknown, the star on the distribution map is positioned mid-country (Fig. 2).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="107" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,152,791]" pageId="8" pageNumber="107">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,513,539]" pageId="8" pageNumber="107">Etymology.</emphasis>
Waterhouse did not cite an etymology, but the specific epithet undoubtedly honored Dr. W. F. Erichson, the author of the genus and a noted, early German entomologist who specialized in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[1174,1301,549,575]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="107" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,152,791]" pageId="8" pageNumber="107">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,584,611]" pageId="8" pageNumber="107">Comments.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Waterhouse, C. O." box="[342,555,585,612]" pageId="8" pageNumber="107" pagination="11 - 25" refId="ref22177" refString="Waterhouse, C. O. (1876) III. On various new genera and species of Coleoptera. Transactions of the Entomological Society of London, 1876 (Part I), 11 - 25. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2311.1876. tb 01122. x" type="journal article" year="1876">Waterhouse (1876)</bibRefCitation>
wrote his description of 
<taxonomicName authority="in Latin" authorityName="in Latin" box="[834,1061,585,611]" class="Insecta" family="Dryopidae" genus="Parygrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erichsoni">
<emphasis box="[834,966,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="107">P. erichsoni</emphasis>
in Latin
</taxonomicName>
followed by an English comparison with the species 
<taxonomicName authority="Fabricius, 1792" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1792" box="[384,816,621,647]" class="Insecta" family="Dryopidae" genus="Parnus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prolifericornis">
<emphasis box="[384,634,621,647]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="107">Parnus prolifericornis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Fabricius, J. C." box="[641,816,621,647]" pageId="8" pageNumber="107" refId="ref21332" refString="Fabricius, J. C. (1792) Entomologica Systematica emendata et aucta. Secundum Classes, Ordines, Genera, Species. Adjectis Synonimis, Locis, Obervationibus, Descriptionibus. Tome 1. Pars 1. C. G. Proft, Hafniae, 330 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 122153" type="book" year="1792">Fabricius, 1792</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Geoffroy, 1785))" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Geoffroy" baseAuthorityYear="1785" box="[973,1399,620,647]" class="Insecta" family="Dryopidae" genus="Dryops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auriculatus">
<emphasis box="[973,1190,621,647]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="107">Dryops auriculatus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Geoffroy, M. M. &amp; Fourcroy, A. F." box="[1204,1380,620,647]" pageId="8" pageNumber="107" refId="ref21396" refString="Geoffroy, M. M. &amp; Fourcroy, A. F. (1785) Entomologia Parisiensis; sive catalogus insectorum quae in Agro Parisiensi reperiuntur; secundum methodum Geoffraeanam in sectiones, genera and species distributus: cui addita funt nomina trivalia &amp; fere trecentae novae Species. Pars prima. Via and Aedibus Serpentineis, Parisiis, 231 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 36528" type="book" year="1785">Geoffroy, 1785</bibRefCitation>
))
</taxonomicName>
. At the end of the Latin description is the line “Long. 2 ¾ lin.; lat. 1 lin.” This is likely the length vs. width body proportions. Waterhouse made no mention of the number of specimens before him. However, the 
<typeStatus box="[1216,1264,693,719]" pageId="8" pageNumber="107">type</typeStatus>
female and associated male have nearly identical locality labels with the same handwriting and were mounted similarly. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Dryopidae" genus="Parygrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erichsoni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="107">Parygrus erichsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the 
<typeStatus box="[329,377,765,791]" pageId="8" pageNumber="107">type</typeStatus>
species of the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
